There was a protest in the Federal Capital Territory, FCT, Abuja, by a coalition of the Civil Society Organisations comprising of over 24 groups to compel President Muhammadu Buhari to assent to the re-worked Electoral Bill.The protesters, who converged on the Unity Fountain in their numbers on Tuesday morning, were said to be heading to the National Assembly Complex.They were sighted with different placards containing different inscriptions such as “Buhari Sign Electoral Bill Now”, “Prevent Elections Rigging”, “The Bill Protects the Voting Rights of PWDS”, “Buhari Save Our Democracy”, among others.Meanwhile, the presidency had early this morning, assured Nigerians that President Buhari would in a matter of hours from now, sign the bill which was transmitted on January 31, 2022, into law.Mr Femi Adesina, Special Adviser to President Buhari on Media and Publicity gave the assurance when he featured on Channels Television programme, Sunrise Daily.protestprotest  source By Chibuike Nwabuko Abuja (Sundiata Post) - The National Chairman of the Nigerian Conscience Party (NCP) and the former Presidential Candidate of the Party in 2019 general election, Dr Yunusa Salisu Tanko has declared his support for a southern president to succeed president Muhammad Buhari come 2023. Dr Tank who… In "Politics" By Taiye Agbaje Abuja  -  Some Nigerians on Tuesday, expressed divergent opinions over “delay’’ by President Muhammadu Buhari in signing the Electoral Act (Amendment) Bill. There have been calls on the president to sign the bill to avoid altering of arrangements for the 2019 elections. The Peoples Democratic Party (PDP)… In "Politics" As the constitutional window closes for President Muhammadu Buhari to sign the Electoral Amendment Bill Nigerians will have to turn to the National Assembly for the next line of action. Although the president has been quiet and failed to communicate his decision on the bill to the legislature, his aides… In "Top Stories"